<s docid="FBIS4-20602" num="15"> CSO [Text] The Earth Observation Center (EOC) of the National Space Development Agency of Japan (NASDA) receives and processes the data from the Japanese Earth Resources Satellite-1 (JERS-1), Marine Observation Satellite-1 and 1b (MOS-1 and 1b), the US Earth observation satellite ``LANDSAT-5,'' French Earth observation satellite ``SPOT-2,'' and the European Remote Sensing Satellite ``ERS-1'' and produces image data.</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-20602" num="16"> The EOC has been conducting Earth observation data analyses since the analyzing equipment was completed in FY 1991 to tackle today's environmental problems.</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-20602" num="17"> The following ten ground truth observations were conducted by EOC and the Remote Sensing Technology Center (RESTEC) to acquire fundamental data for conducting such an analysis and to contribute to the development of future Earth observation sensors.</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-20602" num="18"> (1) JERS-1 and ERS-1 Validation Experiment (Within EOC, and 5 locations including Shizuoka Prefecture) (During and after April 1992) (2) Marine Observation Experiment (the Sea of Kumano and Toba Bay) (From May 22 to May 26, 1992) (3) Kushiro Marshland Observation Equipment (Kushiro Marshland) (June, August, and September 1992) (4) Survey on Observation Requirements for Future Sensors (Tanegashima) (From July 7 to July 10, 1992) (5) Air-Borne X-Band Synthetic Aperture Radar (SAR) Data Acquisition (Tsukuba) (From August 17 to August 19, 1992) (6) Advanced Earth Observing Satellite (ADEOS) Advanced Visible and Near Infrared Radiometer (AVNIR) Validation Experiment (Yadagawa) (From October 16 to October 23, 1992) (7) Disaster Monitoring Mission Experiment (Mt.</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-20602" num="19"> Unzen) (November 2 to November 9, 1992) (8) ERS-1 Marine Observation Experiment (Off Wakayama) (November 27 to December 1) (9) International Space Year (ISY) Sea Ice Observation Experiment (From February 16 to February 21, 1993) (10) Truth Data Acquisition Experiment using Buoys for Ocean Color and Temperature Scanner (OCTS) and NASA/NROSS Scatterometer (NSCAT) (Moji Harbor) (From February 22 to February 27, 1992) The ninth experiment conducted in FY 1992, ``ISY Sea Ice Observation Experiment,'' is outlined here.</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-20602" num="20"> The experiment was conducted in February when drift ice reaches the coast of the Sea of Okhotsk.</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-20602" num="21"> Its purpose was to acquire data for the development and research of marine observation technology.</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-20602" num="22"> Ground truth observation and aerial observation for satellite-synchronous marine observation experiment were conducted using the Side Looking Airborne Radar (SLAR) and an airborne laser altimeter.</s>

<s docid="FBIS4-20602" num="23"> The Drift Ice Laboratory of Hokkaido University, the Hokkaido University of Education, the Communications Research Laboratory (CRL) of the Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications, the First Regional Maritime Safety Headquarters of the Maritime Safety Agency, and the Lake Saroma Fish-Raising Industries Cooperative participated in the experiment.</s>
